<section xml:id="sec-multiplying-and-dividing-irrational-numbers" original="PREALG/modules/m81397/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Multiplying and Dividing Irrational Numbers</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Multiplying and dividing rational numbers (no rationalisation yet) - e.g. sqrt(6) * sqrt(3) = sqrt(18) = 3sqrt(2) - e.g. sqrt(10) / 2 sqrt(5) = sqrt(2)/2 -->

  <objectives>
 Perform operations on irrational numbers in different situations
  </objectives>

  <!-- Add <insight> here -->

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PREALG fs-id1169147967415: Multiply Radical Expressions -->
  
  <p>We have used the <term>Product Property of Roots</term> to simplify square roots by removing the perfect square factors. We can use the Product Property of Roots ‘in reverse’ to multiply square roots. Remember, we assume all variables are greater than or equal to zero.</p>
  
  <p>We will rewrite the Product Property of Roots so we see both ways together.</p>
  
  <insight xml:id="PREALG-RQLdZUgR7W" original="PREALG/modules/m81397/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Product Property of Roots</title>
      <p>For any real numbers, <m>\sqrt[n]{a}</m> and <m>\sqrt[n]{b},</m> and for any integer <m>n \ge 2</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>\sqrt[n]{ab}=\sqrt[n]{a} \cdot \sqrt[n]{b}\text{ and }\sqrt[n]{a} \cdot \sqrt[n]{b}=\sqrt[n]{ab}</me>
      </p>
    </insight>
  
  <p>When we multiply two radicals they must have the same index. Once we multiply the radicals, we then look for factors that are a power of the index and simplify the radical whenever possible.</p>
  
  <p>Multiplying radicals with coefficients is much like multiplying variables with coefficients. To multiply <m>4x \cdot 3y</m> we multiply the coefficients together and then the variables. The result is 12<em>xy</em>. Keep this in mind as you do these examples.</p>
  
  <example xml:id="PREALG-cumgLu3Y4z" original="PREALG/modules/m81397/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <m>(6\sqrt{2})(3\sqrt{10})</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>(−5\sqrt[3]{4})(−4\sqrt[3]{6}).</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>(62)(310) Multiply using the Product Property. 1820 Simplify the radical. 184·5 Simplify. 18·2·5 365</li>
          <li>(−543)(−463) Multiply using the Product Property. 20243 Simplify the radical. 2083·33 Simplify. 20·2·33 4033</li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <p>We follow the same procedures when there are variables in the radicands.</p>
  
  <example xml:id="PREALG-OmZqkIsoGC" original="PREALG/modules/m81397/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <m>(10\sqrt{6p^{3}})(4\sqrt{3p})</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>(2\sqrt[4]{20y^{2}})(3\sqrt[4]{28y^{3}}).</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>(106p3)(43p) Multiply. 4018p4 Simplify the radical. 409p4·2 Simplify. 40·3p2·2 120p22</li>
          <li>When the radicands involve large numbers, it is often advantageous to factor them in order to find the perfect powers.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>(220y24)(328y34) Multiply. 64·5·4·7y54 Simplify the radical. 616y44·35y4 Simplify. 6·2y35y4 Multiply. 12y35y4</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-multiplying-and-dividing-irrational-numbers" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-prealgebra-bundle/tree/7fcdabf0364f3b308c0190557dfc961b579b374c/modules/m81397/index.cnxml">Multiply Radical Expressions</url>" in Open STAX Elementary Algebra 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
